h3. Problem Definition

Allow the "My Review" Dashboard in Crucible to have a customisable filter. This will allow the user to have control over which reviews are displayed, for example;  

The ability to see both outgoing and incoming reviews;

!crucible.dashboard.png|thumbnail!

The ability to show only reviews that are not older than a specific date.

Replace old JDBC with new one which support Oracle12c.
This is required to omit following log entry:

{code}
/atlassian-fisheyectl-2015-07-02.log:2015-07-02 15:11:25,872 INFO [main ] org.hibernate.engine.jdbc.JdbcSupportLoader JdbcSupportLoader-useContextualLobCreation - Disabling contextual LOB creation as createClob() method threw error : java.lang.reflect.InvocationTargetException
{code}

If you have some very long word, that word will exceed available area
!css-bad.png|thumbnail!
My proposal is to add this rule to css:

{code}
#snippet-root-pane ol.source li > pre {
  word-wrap: break-word;
}
{code}
and the result will be:
!css-good.png|thumbnail!

When creating review for a particular changset, Crucible uses commit message to prepopulate review title.  It truncates long messages, but somewhat differently to the git recommendation.

See http://git-scm.com/docs/git-commit#_discussion
{quote}
Though not required, it’s a good idea to begin the commit message with a single short (less than 50 character) line summarizing the change, followed by a blank line and then a more thorough description. The text up to the first blank line in a commit message is treated as the commit title, and that title is used throughout Git. For example, git-format-patch[1] turns a commit into email, and it uses the title on the Subject line and the rest of the commit in the body.
{quote}
